// @test: run
// @level: L0
// @tier: 2
// @tags: codegen, aot, mount-core, main-return-propagation
// @timeout: 480000
// @expected-exit: 7
// @description: AOT mount-core main() return propagation regression.
//
// 2026-04-26 #106: `mount core.*; fn main() -> Int { 7 }` returned
// exit=0 instead of 7. Root cause: Phase 2 body lowering deduped by
// raw VBC name only, skipping ALL but the LAST occurrence per name.
// User's 0-arity `main` collided with stdlib's 2-arity
// `darwin_entry.main(argc, argv)` (in core/sys/init.vr) because the
// blanket "main" → "verum_main" rename hits both. The arity-collision
// path then emits two different LLVM functions (unsuffixed
// `verum_main` and `verum_main__arity2`), but the dedupe — keyed on
// name alone — saw count=2 and dropped one body. With user's main
// first in iteration order, the unsuffixed `verum_main` was left
// bodyless → Phase 3.6 safety net stubbed it as `return 0`.
//
// Fix (672dd8e4) — dedupe key is now (raw_name, arity). Different
// arities map to different LLVM functions and must not be deduped.
//
// This test pins the contract: a user-level main returning a literal
// constant under `mount core.*` must propagate that value through to
// the process exit code.

mount core.*;

fn main() -> Int {
    7
}
